KW  - Entrepreneurship
KW  - Crisis
KW  - Occupational disorientation
KW  - Entrepreneurial self-permission
KW  - Entrepreneurial play
KW  - Possible futures
AB  - This qualitative study explores how individuals try on entrepreneurship during crisis. We discover that individuals use entrepreneurship as a way to envision a possible future in a moment when their occupational trajectory is upended. We reveal that, when a crisis generates a sense of occupational disorientation, individuals are driven to regain control over their future, awakening latent entrepreneurial interests. Yet, our participants needed entrepreneurial self-permission — an emotional, social, and temporal justification for themselves — to engage in entrepreneurial play, experimenting with a possible entrepreneurial identity and potential venture ideas. Altogether, our findings contribute to the growing stream of research on entrepreneurship during crises while offering insight and nuance on broader topics in the field, including entrepreneurial action, decision-making, and identity play.
Executive summary
Crises — low-probability, high-impact occurrences that can devastate or even decimate affected individuals, organizations, and communities — are on the rise, in severity, rate, and complexity. In response, a growing literature examines how individuals, often victims of the crisis themselves, engage in emergent, entrepreneurial behavior during or immediately following crisis. To date, the literature on crisis venturing has focused predominantly on those who venture based on dire need (those who have lost homes or means to survive, for example), and those who venture in response to an opportunity surfaced by the crisis. In all of these cases, crisis venturing is urgent, compelling, and an obvious course of action. While these entrepreneurial responses to crisis are critical to understand, our study focuses on an understudied, third scenario: individuals who experience occupational loss due to crisis, without necessarily experiencing full livelihood upheaval or loss. These individuals suddenly find themselves job-less, for an indeterminate period, but they are still able to survive, relying on a safety net of some kind (whether institutional, family, savings, etc.). In such cases, these individuals may experience what we call crisis triggered “occupational disorientation” — a sudden and unexpected loss of a clear career path. This undertheorized category is important because one of the predominant ways crises affect individuals is job loss, which can disrupt occupational trajectories and trigger disorientation, and these individuals, too, may turn to entrepreneurship. However, with the crisis being neither life threatening nor opportunity revealing (for them), the choice is not an obvious one, and their foray into entrepreneurship under these conditions is likely to be distinct and produce different outcomes. We argue “occupationally disoriented” individuals may utilize times of crisis to “try on” entrepreneurship as a possible future and to cope with the uncertainty the crisis raises, yet we know little about what this might look like.
